Iris classification with scikit-learn¶

Here we use the well-known Iris species dataset to illustrate how Shap can explain the output of many different model types, from k-nearest neighbors, to neural networks. This dataset is very small, with only a 150 samples. We use a random set of 130 for training and 20 for testing the models. Rather than try and predict among three classes, we only try to predict if a flower is of the 'setosa' type. While we only have a few samples, the prediction problem is fairly easy and all methods acheive perfect accuracy.

Setup to classify if the iris is of type 'setosa'¶

In [1]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn import datasets
import scipy as sp
import shap
from shap import KernelExplainer, visualize
import logging
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
% matplotlib inline

iris = datasets.load_iris()
iris_X = iris.data
iris_y = iris.target == 0 # is the target 'setosa'

# Split iris data in train and test data
# A random permutation, to split the data randomly
np.random.seed(0)
indices = np.random.permutation(len(iris_X))
iris_X_train = iris_X[indices[:-20]]
iris_y_train = iris_y[indices[:-20]]
iris_X_test  = iris_X[indices[-20:]]
iris_y_test  = iris_y[indices[-20:]]

def print_accuracy(f):
    print("Accuracy = {0}%".format(100*np.sum(f(iris_X_test) == iris_y_test)/len(iris_y_test)))

iris_data = shap.DenseData(iris_X_train, iris.feature_names)

shap.initjs()

K-nearest neighbors¶

In [2]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()
knn.fit(iris_X_train, iris_y_train)

print_accuracy(knn.predict)

Accuracy = 100.0%

Explain a single prediction from the test set¶

In [3]:
def tovec(f):
    return lambda x: f(x)[:,1]

explaination = KernelExplainer(tovec(knn.predict_proba), iris_data, nsamples=100).explain(iris_X_test[0:1,:])
visualize(explaination)

Support vector machine with a linear kernel¶

Interestingly a linear SVM uses features in a very similar way as KNN. Likely because this is a fairly straightforward classification problem.

In [6]:
from sklearn import svm
svc_linear = svm.SVC(kernel='linear', probability=True)
svc_linear.fit(iris_X_train, iris_y_train)
print_accuracy(svc_linear.predict)

# explain all the predictions in the test set
explainer = KernelExplainer(tovec(svc_linear.predict_proba), iris_data, nsamples=100)
visualize([explainer.explain(iris_X_test[i:i+1,:]) for i in range(20)])

Accuracy = 100.0%

Support vector machine with a radial basis function kernel¶

When we use a nonlinear RBF kernel for the SVM it begins to make more complicated decisions, still with perfect accuracy. Since the simpler models also obtained perfect accuracy it is likely the RBF SVM is beginning to overfit.

In [7]:
from sklearn import svm
svc_rbf = svm.SVC(kernel='rbf', probability=True)
svc_rbf.fit(iris_X_train, iris_y_train)
print_accuracy(svc_rbf.predict)

# explain all the predictions in the test set
explainer = KernelExplainer(tovec(svc_rbf.predict_proba), iris_data, nsamples=100)
visualize([explainer.explain(iris_X_test[i:i+1,:]) for i in range(20)])

Accuracy = 100.0%
